  "summary": "Leo Aigle and Philip Darland discuss the family's children and the implications of the reopened police case. After Mickey leaves to find Tina, Philip questions Leo about the children's adoptions and their consciences. Leo reveals that while Mary's adoption was formal, the others were brought into the family through less official means: Jacques was an orphan left by his grandmother; Mickey was a child whose mother was paid to leave him; Tina’s mother is unknown and unreachable; and Hester is the daughter of an Irish nurse who sent her to Leo and Rachel to hide her from her husband. Leo reflects on Rachel’s desire to mother them all but believes blood ties create an intuition that adoption cannot replicate. Philip suggests that Tina, who is of mixed race, might be withholding information that could harm someone. When Leo admits he fears what a full investigation might reveal, Philip wonders if Leo knows the identity of the perpetrator.\n\nLater, Philip encounters Hester leaning out of a window. Following a cynical exchange regarding suicide, Hester mentions that Mickey used the window as a secret escape route. Hester asks to speak with Philip, noting that Mary does not understand her. In Philip's room, he discusses his past as a pilot and his experience with disability. Hester expresses deep distress, stating that a recent situation is far worse than a simple fight and will never be resolved.",
